Case Study: Phishing Attack

What Phishing Attack is:

Phishing Attack is a thing that people do on the internet where they pretend to be people or organizations that you trust. They try to trick you into giving them information like your password or bank details. They do this by lying to you and using tricks on you than actually hacking into things.

How Phishing Attack typically happens step by step:

- The bad person makes an email or website that looks just like a real one, like a bank or university website.

- You get a message that says you have to do something away like your account is going to be closed or you won a prize.

- The message has a link or file in it.

- When you click on the link you go to a page where you have to log in.

- You put in your information and the bad person gets it.

Who usually gets targeted by Phishing Attack:

Phishing Attack usually targets students, people who work and regular people who use the internet. These are people who may not be very careful when they click on links. The bad people like to pretend to be banks, universities and online stores.

What happens when you get targeted by Phishing Attack:

If you get tricked by Phishing Attack you might lose money someone might steal your identity or someone might get into your accounts. If you are a student someone might get into your school records. Steal your personal information. This can also hurt the organizations that people trust and can cause problems with peoples information.

Example:

In the year 2020 Google said they stopped over 100 million Phishing Attack emails every day. This shows how common and bad Phishing Attack is.

Things to do to stay safe from Phishing Attack if you are a student in India:

- Use an unique password for each account do not use the same password for everything.

- Turn on two-factor authentication on your email, media and banking apps.

- Check links before you click on them in emails, WhatsApp or text messages.

- Do not use Wi-Fi when you are doing things that need to be secret like banking or paying bills.

- Be careful when someone asks you for money through UPI do not say yes if you do not know who it is.

- Check the name of the person or store before you pay them through UPI bad people might be pretending to be a store.

- Keep your phone and apps up to date this will help keep you safe.

- Do not share much information about yourself online be careful what you put on social media.

Where to report if you get targeted by Phishing Attack:

- National Cyber Crime Portal: cybercrime.gov.in

- Helpline number: 1930

